===Adjective===
{{en-adj|smoother|smoothest}}

# Having a texture that lacks [[friction]].  Not [[rough]].
#*{{quote-book|year=2005|author=Lesley Brown|title=Sophist|extra=[[w:Stephanus pagination|229e]]|by=[[w:Plato|Plato]]
|passage=Teaching that’s done by talking seems to have one rough path and another part which is '''smoother'''.}}
# Without [[difficulty]], [[problems]], or [[unexpected]] consequences or incidents.
#: ''We hope for a '''smooth''' transition to the new system.''
# [[bland]]; [[glib]]
#* {{quote-book|year=1912|author=Gustavus Myers|title=History of the Supreme Court of the United States|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Mt89AAAAIAAJ|page=133
|passage=This feeling, grounded on the experience of centuries of oppression, was not to be allayed by '''smooth''' explanations on the part of the advocates of the Constitution.}}
# {{context|of a person}} [[suave]]; [[sophisticated]]
#* {{quote-book|year=2003|author=T. Lewis Humphrey|title=The Price of Love|isbn=0595272606|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=vjavgdWaY8kC|page=279
|passage=He was so '''smooth''' and handsome. He knew just what to say and when to say it.}}
# {{context|of an action}} [[natural]]; [[unconstrained]]
#* {{quote-book|year=2006|title=Reading for Fluency|author=Mary Kay Moskal and Camille Blachowicz|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ZHWaNQqTMLwC|isbn=1593852649|page=3
|passage=In order for a reading to be '''smooth''' and effortless, readers must be able to recognize and read words accurately, automatically, and quickly.}}
# {{context|of a motion}} [[unbroken]]
#* {{quote-book|year=1927|author=United States National Guard Bureau|title=Manual of Basic Training and Standards of Proficiency for the National Guard
|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=uwxIAAAAIAAJ|page=181
|passage=Demonstrate first by the numbers and then as one '''smooth''' movement.}}
# {{especially|of water}} [[placid]], calm.
#* {{quote-book|year=1898|author=John Donaldson Ford|title=An American Cruiser in the East|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=5G5CAAAAIAAJ|page=47
|passage=As we worked to the southward, we picked up fair weather, and enjoyed '''smooth''' seas and pleasant skies.}}
# {{context|of an edge}} [[lack|Lacking]] [[projection]]s or [[indentation]]s; not [[serrated]].
#* {{quote-book|year=1994|author=Robert E. Swanson|title=A Field Guide to the Trees and Shrubs of the Southern Appalachians|isbn=0801845564|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=0wxY2k8TS_wC|page=8
|passage=A leaf having a '''smooth''' margin, without teeth or indentations of any kind, is called entire.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1997|author=Christopher Dickey|title=Innocent Blood: A Novel|isbn=0684842009|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=qpdZZ9y9DxUC|page=91
|passage=Out of the handles flipped the '''smooth''' blade and the serrated blade, which was dangerously sharp, the flathead screwdrivers, the Phillips screwdriver, the can opener, the awl.}}
# {{context|of food or drink}} Not [[grainy]]; having an [[even]] texture.
#* {{quote-book|year=1997|author=Lou Seibert Pappas|title=Sorbets and Ice Creams|isbn=0811815730|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=MQ7gxYAz0OoC|page=19
|passage=A compact and stylish design, it produces 1 generous quart of excellent, '''smooth''' ice cream in 20 to 25 minutes.}}
# {{context|of a beverage}} Having a [[pleasant]]ly [[rounded]] flavor; neither [[rough]] nor [[astringent]].
#* {{quote-book|year=2002|author=Candace Irvin|title=For His Eyes Only|isbn=0373079362|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=gfFrU4YJ-8oC|page=9
|passage=The coffee was '''smooth''', so smooth she took another sip.}}
# {{mathematics|of a function}} Having [[derivative]]s of all [[finite]] [[order]]s at all points within the function’s [[domain]].
#* {{quote-book|year=2003|author=Eric W. Weisstein|title=CRC Concise Encyclopedia of Mathematics|isbn=1584883472|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=taoW6K3sFfUC&|page=419
|passage=Any ANALYTIC FUNCTION is '''smooth'''. But a smooth function is not necessarily analytic.}}
# {{linguistics|classical studies|of a vowel}} Lacking marked [[aspiration]].
#* {{quote-book|year=1830|author=Benjamin Franklin Fisk|title=A Grammar of the Greek Language|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=_rQRAAAAIAAJ|page=5
|passage=''{{IPAchar|Ου}}'' becomes ''{{IPAchar|οὐκ}}'' before a '''smooth''' vowel, and ''{{IPAchar|οὐχ}}'' before an aspirate.}}

